  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the food eating challenges in India?",
  "response": "India is known for its diverse and flavorful cuisine, and over the years, several food eating challenges have gained popularity across the country. These challenges test the mettle of food enthusiasts and spice lovers. Here are some notable ones:\n\n1. **Desi Gutkha at Taareef, Pune**: Participants must eat a gigantic platter that includes a variety of rich Mughlai dishes, naan, and dessert within a set time.\n\n2. **The Bada Pao Challenge at Shiv Tikki Wala, Delhi**: This involves consuming five massive wada pavs, each loaded with a spicy aloo patty, in a limited time.\n\n3. **Bahubali Thali at Aaoji Khaoji, Pune**: Named after the popular movie, this thali includes a significant number of dishes and weighs over 8 kilograms. Participants must finish it in one sitting.\n\n4. **The Spice Challenge at Naga Reddy\u2019s, Hyderabad**: Known for its fiery dishes, this challenge requires participants to consume extremely spicy Indian curries and biryanis.\n\n5. **Dosa Marathon at 196 Degress Below, Bangalore**: Here, participants try to eat as many dosas as they can within a set timeframe. The dosas are served continuously until the eater taps out.\n\n6. **Lal Maas Challenge in Jaipur**: In this challenge, participants have to finish a serving of Lal Maas, a traditional Rajasthani dish known for its extreme spiciness.\n\n7. **Sardar\u2019s Pav Bhaji in Mumbai**: Competitors must finish a massive plate of richly buttered and spicy pav bhaji within a limited time frame.\n\n8. **Punjabi Thali Challenge at Amritsar**: Known for its heavy and rich dishes, this challenge involves finishing a gigantic Punjabi thali loaded with multiple traditional dishes.\n\n9. **Bhoot Jolokia Challenge in Northeast India**: This challenge involves eating food flavored with Bhut Jolokia or Ghost Pepper, one of the hottest peppers in the world.\n\n10. **The Great Indian Thali Challenge at Delhi**: Often includes more than 30 items in a single thali, and participants have to finish it all in record time.\n\nThese challenges not only offer a fun and exciting experience, but they also provide insight into India's culinary diversity, showcasing local and regional food specialties. However, they can be quite extreme, especially for those not accustomed to spicy or large quantities of food.",
